umanism which gained significant popularity in Victorian Canada, Alice Chown was in many ways a woman very much of her time. She was also far ahead of it: to feminist and pacifist ears today, the voice in The Stairway rings true.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFeministszCanadavDiaries. 0aPacifistszCanadavDiaries. 0aRadicalszCanadavDiaries. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh1 aChown, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChown, Diana.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265276740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442652767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442652767.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK